const faqSchema = { '@context': 'https://schema.org', '@type': 'FAQPage', mainEntity: [
  { '@type': 'Question', name: 'Does biotin help with beard growth?', acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Biotin (vitamin B7) is a cofactor for carboxylase enzymes involved in keratin protein synthesis. Since beard hair is composed primarily of keratin, adequate biotin supports the structural protein production required for beard growth. However, clinical evidence specifically for beard growth is limited — most studies focus on hair thinning and nail brittleness. Biotin supplementation is most effective when there is an underlying biotin deficiency. Men with patchy beards due to genetics (DHT receptor density, androgen sensitivity) are unlikely to see dramatic improvement from biotin alone. That said, many men report subjective improvements in beard thickness and growth rate with 5,000-10,000mcg daily biotin supplementation over 3-6 months.' } },
  { '@type': 'Question', name: 'How much biotin should men take for hair and beard?', acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'The Adequate Intake (AI) for biotin is 30mcg per day for adults. However, most hair and beard growth supplements provide 2,500-10,000mcg (83-333 times the AI). There is no established Tolerable Upper Intake Level for biotin because toxicity has not been observed at high doses — biotin is water-soluble and excess is excreted in urine. For beard and hair growth, most clinical trials and dermatologist recommendations use 2,500-5,000mcg daily. Some products offer 10,000mcg, but there is no evidence that doses above 5,000mcg provide additional benefit. Start at 2,500-5,000mcg and assess results after 3-6 months.' } },
  { '@type': 'Question', name: 'Does biotin cause acne in men?', acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'There are anecdotal reports and some dermatological case studies linking high-dose biotin (5,000-10,000mcg) supplementation with acne breakouts, particularly along the jawline and chin. The proposed mechanism involves biotin competing with pantothenic acid (vitamin B5) for intestinal absorption — since B5 is important for skin barrier function and sebum regulation, reduced B5 absorption may increase sebum production and trigger breakouts. This is not universal and affects only a subset of users. If you experience acne after starting biotin, try reducing the dose to 2,500mcg or adding a B5 supplement (500mg) to counterbalance. Staying well-hydrated and maintaining a consistent skincare routine also helps.' } },
  { '@type': 'Question', name: 'How long does biotin take to work for beard growth?', acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Beard and hair growth operate on a biological timeline that cannot be accelerated beyond certain limits. The hair growth cycle includes anagen (active growth phase, 2-6 years for scalp hair, shorter for beard hair), catagen (transition, 2-3 weeks), and telogen (rest/shedding, 2-3 months). Biotin supports the anagen phase by optimizing keratin synthesis, but you will not see visible results until new hairs complete enough growth cycles to become visible. Most men report noticeable improvements in beard density and thickness after 3-6 months of consistent daily biotin supplementation. Some notice improved nail strength earlier (6-8 weeks), which serves as an early indicator that biotin is being utilized.' } },
  { '@type': 'Question', name: 'What ingredients work with biotin for men\'s hair?', acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Several ingredients complement biotin for men\'s hair and beard growth: (1) Zinc — required for cell division in hair follicles and regulates DHT metabolism. (2) Saw palmetto — may inhibit 5-alpha-reductase, reducing DHT conversion (relevant for men experiencing androgenic hair thinning). (3) Collagen — provides amino acids (proline, glycine) for hair protein structure. (4) Vitamin D — deficiency is linked to alopecia; maintaining adequate levels supports hair cycling. (5) Iron — ferritin deficiency is a common cause of hair shedding in men. (6) MSM (methylsulfonylmethane) — provides sulfur for keratin disulfide bonds. Look for men\'s formulas combining biotin with at least 2-3 of these synergistic ingredients.' } },
  { '@type': 'Question', name: 'Does biotin interfere with blood tests?', acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Yes — this is a critical safety consideration. High-dose biotin (5,000mcg and above) can interfere with immunoassay-based laboratory tests, potentially causing falsely elevated thyroid hormone levels, falsely low TSH readings, falsely low troponin results (cardiac marker), and inaccurate hormone panels. The FDA issued a safety communication in 2017 warning about biotin interference with lab tests. If you are taking biotin supplements, inform your healthcare provider before any blood work and consider discontinuing biotin for 48-72 hours before lab tests to avoid interference. This is especially important for thyroid panels, cardiac troponin tests, and hormone level assessments.' } },
] };
