    <h2 id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions About Biotin Gummies for Men</h2>
    <details class="fq"><summary>Does biotin help with beard growth?</summary><p>Biotin supports keratin synthesis — the structural protein of beard hair. Most effective when biotin deficiency exists. Genetics (androgen receptor density) remain the primary determinant of beard thickness. 5,000mcg daily for 3-6 months is the typical recommendation.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>How much biotin should men take for hair and beard?</summary><p>2,500-5,000mcg daily is the standard dermatologist recommendation. No evidence that 10,000mcg outperforms 5,000mcg. Biotin is water-soluble with no established upper limit, but higher doses increase lab test interference risk.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>Does biotin cause acne in men?</summary><p>Some men experience jawline breakouts at high doses. Biotin may compete with vitamin B5 for absorption, reducing B5's skin-protective effects. Counter with 500mg B5 supplementation, adequate hydration, and consistent skincare.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>How long does biotin take to work for beard growth?</summary><p>3-6 months minimum. Beard growth cycles are slower than scalp hair. Improved nail strength (6-8 weeks) is often the first visible sign that biotin is being utilized. Photograph monthly for objective comparison.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>What ingredients work with biotin for men's hair?</summary><p>Saw palmetto (DHT reduction), zinc (cell division + DHT metabolism), vitamin D (hair cycling), ashwagandha (cortisol/stress shedding), collagen (amino acids for hair protein), and MSM (sulfur for keratin bonds). Multi-ingredient formulas outperform biotin alone.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>Does biotin interfere with blood tests?</summary><p>Yes. FDA warned in 2017 that biotin at 5,000mcg and above causes falsely elevated thyroid hormones, falsely low TSH, and inaccurate cardiac troponin. Stop biotin 48-72 hours before blood work. Inform your healthcare provider about supplementation.</p></details>

